<h1>Problem 1230 - 2021 IMOSL, G3 v1, CG</h1>
<h2 class='difficulty'>Difficulty: 8</h2>
<p>Let \(n\) be a fixed positive integer, and let \(\textbf{S}\) be the set of points \((x,y)\) on the Cartesian plane such that both coordinates \(x\) and \(y\) are nonnegative integers smaller than \(2n\) (thus \(|\textbf{S}| = 4n^2\)). Assume that \(\mathcal{F}\) is a set consisting of \(n^2\) quadrilaterals such that all their vertices lie in \(\textbf{S}\), and each point in \(\textbf{S}\) is a vertex of exactly one of the quadrilaterals in \(\mathcal{F}\). Determine the largest possible sum of areas of all \(n^2\) quadrilaterals in \(\mathcal{F}\).</p>
